# Storybook convention

- Each component lives in its own file src/components/{ComponentName}/{ComponentName}.stories.tsx (CSF format).
- Use autodocs `(tags: ['autodocs'])`.
- Include a short MDX description at the top (<Meta of="{ComponentName}" />) if additional usage notes are required.
- Export the component’s prop types in the docs table automatically; no manual tables.

# Storybook args & controls guidelines

- Expose every public prop (except `className`, `style`, and `data‑*`) via Storybook Controls.
- For enum‑like props, provide a union type and set the control to radio or select.
- Organise controls alphabetically; hide internal/technical props with `table: { disable: true }`.

# Storybook minimal example guidelines

- Supply at least two stories:

| Story                              | Purpose                                   | Required? |
| ---------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | --------- |
| `Playground`                       | fully controllable example, bound to args | Yes       |
| `Primary` (or design‑spec default) | canonical look                            | Yes       |
| `WithIcon`, `Compact`, etc.        | edge cases                                | Optional  |

- Use the Template pattern for re‑use:
  ```ts
    const Template: StoryFn<{ComponentName}Props> = args => <{ComponentName} {...args} />
  ```
